Claude List, born on December 2, 1902, in Maryborough, Queensland, Australia, was the youngest of three children to Heinrich (Henry) Wilschefski and Mary Frances Carter. His father was German, and his mother was English, both of whose families had immigrated to Australia in the late 1800s. Henry passed away when Claude was 11 months old, and his mother remarried Francis Martin List in 1907, with whom she had five more children. The family moved to New Zealand between 1915 and 1919, living in Glen Eden by 1919.

Claude began playing rugby league in Queensland at around 10 years old, in 1912. After moving to New Zealand, he played for the Kingsland Rovers' third grade side, which he joined in 1921 at the age of 18. His older brother Percy, aged 22, may have also been part of the team. The Kingsland Rovers won the 3rd grade championship in 1921, and Claude continued to play for their 3rd grade side in the 1922 season, where they were runners-up. He was listed as "C List" in the team, with another List, possibly his brother Percy, listed as "J List".

In 1921, Claude List, then 18, and his brother Percy, 22, played for the Kingsland Rovers' third grade team, which won the championship that year. The following season, they remained on the third grade side, now with Claude listed as "C List" and Percy as "J List," finishing as runners-up. By 1923, Claude advanced to the Kingsland 2nd grade side. In 1924, he played on the wing for the 2nd grade side, winning the knockout competition and excelling in matches against Hamilton and Devonport United juniors. The 1925 season marked Claude's senior debut for Kingsland in the B Division and his selection for the Auckland junior representative side. He made an impressive debut, scoring three tries against Northcote & Birkenhead Rangers. This breakthrough year led to his selection for the national side in 1928, making him the first player chosen from a second-division side in New Zealand history.
